   <text>
      <body>
         <div>
            <head>4.9.1882 Montag</head>
            <p>
               <placeName type="write" key="48915">Etretat</placeName> September 4 1882
                  Monday</p>
            <p>
               <persName key="103">Mamma</persName> and were walking on the road to <placeName key="48926">les Ifs</placeName> today, when we saw some smoke coming out of a
               chump of trees; we walked up to them and there saw a good sized house one mass of
               flames; the poor people who lived in it were crying, while the people of <placeName key="50318">Bordeaux</placeName> were standing about gossiping and telling those
               whose house was burning that of course everything would be burnt but that they ought
               to be thankful that it did not happen in the night. The fire-engine had been sent for
               to <placeName key="48918">les Loges</placeName> and <placeName key="48915">Etretat</placeName>. The <placeName key="48918">Loges</placeName> engines arrived
               at about 6.30 and the bags with the folding canvas pails were immediately opened and
               each of us got a pail and fetched water amidst the screams of &#x201e;de l&#x2019;eau, allons de
               l&#x2019;eau,&#x201c;; but everything was very disorganized till we were told to make &#x201e;la chaine&#x201c;
               that is to stand in two rows: one to pass the filled buckets to the engine, the other
               to pass back the empty ones. At a little past seven <persName key="103">Mamma</persName> went away and at about half past the <placeName key="48915">Etretat</placeName> engine arrived but could not do much good as almost all the
               water in the place was exhausted, the little that was left being more or less
               monopolized by the <placeName key="48918">Loges</placeName> people. I went away at
               about 8.15. and met <persName key="877">François</persName>, who took me home on the road.</p>
